is necessary to maintain a critical attitude. If one 
is really serious about the individual freedoms of 
people, one must also respect them as individuals. 
One must then aid them to a freedom which does 
not remain bound to the modern ideal of emanci-
pation in society alone, 60 but beyond that keeps 
open the possibility that human, living beings with 
their individual characteristics can live outside so-
ciety. 61 In the end, it is a matter of preventing even 
more people from falling victim to the law, if they 
pay the price "of a permanent alienation or even 
enslavement of people in the name of a compulso-
