by Franz Wieacker's model of a material ethics of 
conscience and responsibility, 71 or by the "politi-
cization" explained by Rudolf Wiethölter, 72 can in 
this respect be left open. Much more decisive is the 
awareness that "materialization" and "politiciza-
tion" must by no means be misunderstood here in 
the sense of a moral-philosophical or state-politi-
cal instruction of free jurists by means of instruc-
tion, even indoctrination from the outside. Rather, 
